<paragraph id="D44EBF23A816F110FF5EFE04FE269B4E" blockId="7.[178,1085,504,556]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">
Description: General appearance as figured (
<figureCitation id="4CCAA3A6A816F110FD32FE04FCD49B6B" box="[734,807,504,526]" captionStart="Figs 10-12" captionStartId="20.[178,218,1478,1500]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-0@20.[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 10-12: Anthracus anichtchenkoi nov.sp. Habitus, head and pronotum. (10) HT, (11) PT, India, Jaspur, (12) PT, Nepal, Nepalgunj." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5193667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5193667/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">Fig 10</figureCitation>
). Body length 
<quantity id="130912C6A816F110FC29FE04FBCE9B6B" box="[965,1085,504,526]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" metricValueMax="3.7" metricValueMin="3.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368" unit="mm" value="3.4" valueMax="3.7" valueMin="3.1">3.1-3.7 mm</quantity>
(HT 3.4); width 
<quantity id="130912C6A816F110FEB4FDEAFE239B4E" box="[344,464,534,555]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368" unit="mm" value="1.45" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.2">1.2-1.7 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A816F110FF5EFDC7FE1F9A3D" blockId="7.[178,1085,571,856]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">
Shiny, pronotum weakly, elytra moderately iridescent. Head and pronotum paler to darker yellowish brown (HT and PT from Jaspur) or reddish yellow (PT from Nepalgunj), with clypeus, labrum and mandibles somewhat paler (inner margin and apices blackish). Elytra darker to paler reddish yellow or yellowish brown, with each elytron having a more or less distinct dark or blackish brown central macula, expanding laterally to interval 
<quantity id="130912C6A816F110FECAFD31FE969B86" box="[294,357,717,739]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.27" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368" unit="in" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5-7 in</quantity>
and leaving the first interval, as well as basal, lateral and apical part reddish yellow or yellowish brown. Legs, palpi and first two antennomeres pale yellowish brown, antennomeres 3-11 moderately infuscated. Ventral surface mainly reddish brown, proepisterna sometimes somewhat darker, and abdominal sternite 4-6 sometimes somewhat paler in central part.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A816F110FF5EFC94FE6D9DE0" blockId="7.[178,1086,872,1157]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">
Head (
<figureCitation id="4CCAA3A6A816F110FF1AFC94FE959A1B" box="[246,358,872,894]" captionStart="Figs 10-12" captionStartId="20.[178,218,1478,1500]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-0@20.[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 10-12: Anthracus anichtchenkoi nov.sp. Habitus, head and pronotum. (10) HT, (11) PT, India, Jaspur, (12) PT, Nepal, Nepalgunj." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5193667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5193667/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">Figs 10-12</figureCitation>
) including eyes 0.81-0.86 times as wide as pronotum, with eyes rather large and distinctly prominent (head 1.63-1.72 times as wide as head between eyes). Labrum almost rectilinear at apical margin, sometimes weakly sloped down to the right side. Mandibles medium sized, left mandible rather sharp at apex, not thickened or truncate. Antennae 2.54-2.55 times as long as pronotum and 0.90-0.91 times as long as elytra. Microsculpture on labrum distinct and almost isodiametric, on clypeus isodiametric to weakly transverse, on frons and anterior half of vertex almost lacking or with traces of very lightly impressed isodiametric meshes, and on posterior half of vertex with lightly impressed isodiametric meshes, becoming weakly transverse in front of pronotal apical margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A816F110FF5EFB69FD0C9F6F" blockId="7.[178,1086,1172,1546]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="4CCAA3A6A816F110FEC8FB68FE609DCE" box="[292,403,1172,1195]" captionStart="Figs 10-12" captionStartId="20.[178,218,1478,1500]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-0@20.[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 10-12: Anthracus anichtchenkoi nov.sp. Habitus, head and pronotum. (10) HT, (11) PT, India, Jaspur, (12) PT, Nepal, Nepalgunj." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5193667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5193667/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">Figs 10-12</figureCitation>
) 1.30-1.32 times as wide as long, 1.17-1.23 times as wide as head, widest in second quarter, lateral seta inserted at beginning of second quarter. Apical margin almost rectilinear or only faintly emarginated, anterior angles narrowly rounded at tips, not or very weakly projecting forward. Sides convex in anterior half, rectilinearly narrowed to posterior angles, which are obtuse and rather widely rounded. Basal margin almost straight or weakly arcuate medially and oblique to posterior angles. Lateral furrows moderately wide anteriorly, becoming weakly widened at posterior third, where they are fused with the baso-lateral impressions. The latter medium sized and somewhat oblique, distinctly delimited from the pronotal disc and median part of base, fused with basal and lateral margins. Anterior transverse impression obsolete, rarely suggested. Microsculpture on disc with fine, moderately to lightly impressed, moderately to strongly transverse meshes, at baso-lateral impressions and lateral furrows with distinctly impressed, weakly transverse to almost isodiametric meshes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A816F11FFF5EF9E5FC939803" blockId="7.[178,1085,1561,1583]" lastBlockId="8.[178,1086,219,358]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="1369" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="4CCAA3A6A816F110FEECF9E5FEBF9F4A" box="[256,332,1561,1583]" captionStart="Figs 10-12" captionStartId="20.[178,218,1478,1500]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetId="figure-0@20.[178,1085,212,1573]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 10-12: Anthracus anichtchenkoi nov.sp. Habitus, head and pronotum. (10) HT, (11) PT, India, Jaspur, (12) PT, Nepal, Nepalgunj." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5193667" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5193667/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="1368">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) with sides slightly to moderately widened posteriorly, widest just at or slightly posterior to middle, 1.54-1.63 times as long as wide, 2.61-2.85 times as long and 1.29-1.40 times as wide as pronotum. Elytral striae distinctly impressed and impunctate, intervals rather flat, becoming somewhat narrowed and very weakly convex at apex. Microsculpture on scutellum and around basal pore with isodiametric meshes, on elytral intervals only with traces of very lightly impressed transverse lines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A819F11FFF5EFE89FD779887" blockId="8.[178,1086,373,483]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">Metepisterna long and narrowed posteriad, at inner margin about 1.5 times longer than wide at basal margin. Prosternum medially with at least 4 and in front of apical margin with 4 medium long setae (often broken and then insertion points difficult to observe). Prosternal process with at least 1 distinct seta.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A819F11FFF5EFE0FFD139B6D" blockId="8.[178,736,498,520]" box="[178,736,498,520]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">
Protarsomeres and mesotarsomeres as in 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFDBEFE0FFD299B62" baseAuthorityName="ANDREWES" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[594,730,498,520]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nesophilus">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFDBEFE0FFD299B62" box="[594,730,498,520]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. nesophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A819F11FFF5EFDE4FDDF9BE0" blockId="8.[178,1085,536,645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">
Median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="4CCAA3A6A819F11FFE23FDE4FDB09B4B" box="[463,579,536,558]" captionStart="Figs 42-49" captionStartId="28.[178,218,1555,1577]" captionTargetBox="[150,1112,189,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-0@28.[150,1112,189,1632]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figs 42-49: Anthracus anichtchenkoi nov.sp. Median lobe of aedoeagus, lateral and dorsal aspect. (42, 45, 47, 49) PT, India, Jaspur, (43, 46) HT, (44, 48) PT, Nepal, Nepalgunj." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5194868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5194868/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">Figs 42-49</figureCitation>
) similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFCF9FDE4FC529B48" baseAuthorityName="ANDREWES" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[789,929,536,557]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nesophilus">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFCF9FDE4FC529B48" box="[789,929,536,557]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. nesophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but markedly smaller, less distinctly curved in central part, and internal sac with a vertical group of 12- 15 medium sized teeth, with the first two teeth in apical part usually somewhat shifted to the right side (seen from 
<figureCitation id="4CCAA3A6A819F11FFE5CFD93FDD29BE0" box="[432,545,623,645]" captionStart="Figs 42-49" captionStartId="28.[178,218,1555,1577]" captionTargetBox="[150,1112,189,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-0@28.[150,1112,189,1632]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figs 42-49: Anthracus anichtchenkoi nov.sp. Median lobe of aedoeagus, lateral and dorsal aspect. (42, 45, 47, 49) PT, India, Jaspur, (43, 46) HT, (44, 48) PT, Nepal, Nepalgunj." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5194868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5194868/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">Figs 46-49</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9CEBECA8A819F11FFF5EFD69FC7C9DC0" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A819F11FFF5EFD69FCE79D6F" blockId="8.[178,1086,661,1034]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">
Comparisons and remarks: 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFD68FD69FC709BCF" authority="Jaeger, 2015" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" box="[644,899,661,682]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anichtchenkoi" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFD68FD69FC709BCF" box="[644,899,661,682]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">Anthracus anichtchenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="FDB6DE4AA819F11FFC67FD69FC279BCF" box="[907,980,661,682]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFEF0FD4EFE549BA2" baseAuthorityName="ANDREWES" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[284,423,690,711]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nesophilus">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFEF0FD4EFE549BA2" box="[284,423,690,711]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. nesophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFE31FD4EFD7A9BA2" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" box="[477,649,690,711]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philippinensis">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFE31FD4EFD7A9BA2" box="[477,649,690,711]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. philippinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from the former by the smaller median lobe of the aedeagus, with different internal structures (the group of teeth is arranged more central, with number of teeth more numerous and the two apical teeth shifted to right side). Externally it can be separated from 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFCF5FCF6FC569A7A" baseAuthorityName="ANDREWES" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[793,933,778,799]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nesophilus">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFCF5FCF6FC569A7A" box="[793,933,778,799]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. nesophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger, more prominent eyes (HW/HWbE 
<quantity id="130912C6A819F11FFDC4FCDBFD5B9A58" box="[552,680,807,829]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.254499999999999" metricValueMax="4.3688" metricValueMin="4.1402" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" unit="in" value="1.6749999999999998" valueMax="1.72" valueMin="1.63">1.63-1.72 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFD5FFCDBFC919A59" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" box="[691,866,807,828]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anichtchenkoi">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFD5FFCDBFC919A59" box="[691,866,807,828]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. anichtchenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<quantity id="130912C6A819F11FFC70FCDBFBEF9A58" box="[924,1052,807,829]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0767" metricValueMax="4.1402" metricValueMin="4.0132" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" unit="in" value="1.605" valueMax="1.63" valueMin="1.58">1.58-1.63 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFBCBFCDBFEED9A3C" baseAuthorityName="ANDREWES" baseAuthorityYear="1936" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nesophilus">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFBCBFCDBFEED9A3C" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. nesophilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and other correlated indices (HW/PW), the not or less emarginated pronotal apical margin, and often also by flatter elytral intervals. From 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFCDFFC9EFC2D9A12" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" box="[819,990,866,887]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philippinensis">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFCDFFC9EFC2D9A12" box="[819,990,866,887]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. philippinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it can be distinguished by the internal structures of the aedeagus, which consist of smaller, more numerous, not very closely arranged teeth with first two apical teeth usually shifted to right side. Externally 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFE7BFC46FDB79AAB" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" box="[407,580,953,975]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anichtchenkoi">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFE7BFC46FDB79AAB" box="[407,580,953,975]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. anichtchenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFD3FFC45FC929AAB" box="[723,865,953,974]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">philippinensis</emphasis>
also by larger, more distinctly produced eyes (HW/HWbE 
<quantity id="130912C6A819F11FFDD1FC2BFD499A88" box="[573,698,983,1005]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.254499999999999" metricValueMax="4.3688" metricValueMin="4.1402" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" unit="in" value="1.6749999999999998" valueMax="1.72" valueMin="1.63">1.63-1.72 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFD2EFC2BFC9D9A89" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" box="[706,878,983,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anichtchenkoi">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFD2EFC2BFC9D9A89" box="[706,878,983,1004]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. anichtchenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<quantity id="130912C6A819F11FFC4EFC2BFBEC9A88" box="[930,1055,983,1005]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.064" metricValueMax="4.1402" metricValueMin="3.9878" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" unit="in" value="1.6" valueMax="1.63" valueMin="1.57">1.57-1.63 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFBCBFC2BFEB39D6C" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philippinensis">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFBCBFC2BFEB39D6C" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. philippinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and related body proportions (e.g. HW/PW).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44EBF23A819F11FFF5EFBE6FC7C9DC0" blockId="8.[178,1086,1049,1189]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">
From 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFF1CFBE6FE2D9D4A" authority="JAEGER, 2015" authorityName="JAEGER" authorityYear="2015" box="[240,478,1049,1071]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="skalei">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFF1CFBE6FEBB9D4B" box="[240,328,1049,1071]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. skalei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B060C2D2A819F11FFEA3FBE6FE2D9D4A" author="JAEGER B" box="[335,478,1049,1071]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" refId="ref12895" refString="JAEGER B. (2015): Two new maculate species of the Anthracus annamensis group from Nepal and adjacent areas (Insecta: Coleoptera: Carabidae: Harpalini: Stenolophina). Pp. 339 - 345. - In: HARTMANN M. &amp; J. WEIPERT (eds), Biodiversitat und Naturausstattung im Himalaya V. - Verein der Freunde und Forderer des Naturkundemuseums Erfurt e. V. Erfurt: 580 pp." type="book" year="2015">JAEGER, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFE05FBE6FD109D4A" authority="JAEGER, 2015" authorityName="JAEGER" authorityYear="2015" box="[489,739,1049,1071]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weigeli">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFE05FBE6FDBC9D4B" box="[489,591,1049,1071]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. weigeli</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B060C2D2A819F11FFDBAFBE6FD109D4A" author="JAEGER B" box="[598,739,1049,1071]" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" refId="ref12895" refString="JAEGER B. (2015): Two new maculate species of the Anthracus annamensis group from Nepal and adjacent areas (Insecta: Coleoptera: Carabidae: Harpalini: Stenolophina). Pp. 339 - 345. - In: HARTMANN M. &amp; J. WEIPERT (eds), Biodiversitat und Naturausstattung im Himalaya V. - Verein der Freunde und Forderer des Naturkundemuseums Erfurt e. V. Erfurt: 580 pp." type="book" year="2015">JAEGER, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and two undescribed taxa closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFEF6FBCBFDF99D29" authority="(BATES)" baseAuthorityName="BATES" box="[282,522,1079,1100]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="annamensis">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFEF6FBCBFE5D9D29" box="[282,430,1079,1100]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. annamensis</emphasis>
(BATES)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFDD2FBCBFCA39D29" authority="(BOHEMAN)" baseAuthorityName="BOHEMAN" box="[574,848,1079,1100]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="biplagiatus">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFDD2FBCBFD3E9D29" box="[574,717,1079,1100]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. biplagiatus</emphasis>
(BOHEMAN)
</taxonomicName>
, which belong to other species complexes but occur also in northern 
<collectingCountry id="ACE6FFB3A819F11FFD6EFBA8FD459D0F" box="[642,694,1108,1130]" name="India" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">India</collectingCountry>
and/or 
<collectingCountry id="ACE6FFB3A819F11FFCE9FBA8FCB79D0F" box="[773,836,1108,1130]" name="Nepal" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, partly sympatrically, 
<taxonomicName id="13F1C4A0A819F11FFBCBFBA8FEB39DE3" authorityName="Jaeger" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Anthracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anichtchenkoi">
<emphasis id="E6856331A819F11FFBCBFBA8FEB39DE3" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="1369">A. anichtchenkoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the peculiar shape of the apical plateau of the aedeagus and the different internal structures (
